The Revival of the Great Leader
London — — The Battle of Waterloo has long since passed, and Napoleon's catastrophic defeat in that battle seriously damaged France's self-respect, to the extent that General de Gaulle omitted any mention of the battle when writing the history of the French army.
Nevertheless, if you accept that "greatness" is a personal quality, then both Napoleon and de Gaulle can be considered among the greatest leaders in history.
Marx and Tolstoy would say that there is no such thing as a "great leader."
In Marx's view, the class struggle in France created the environment in which a "strange mediocrity" like Napoleon could become a hero.
In Tolstoy's view, Napoleon was not particularly outstanding as a general; his victories should be credited to the courage and devotion of the French soldiers who won the Battle of Borodino.
Regardless of whether Napoleon was great, we must determine whether it is possible to describe any leader as great.
If the answer is yes, then who can be described as great?
Political philosopher Isaiah Berlin believes that great leaders must meet two particularly important criteria.
First, can this leader recognize historical trends?
Otto von Bismarck did, and his German compatriot Konrad Adenauer; using Bismarck's memorable phrase, both heard the "sound of the divine cloak."
Secondly, did this leader make important decisions?
Of course, if a leader is forced to make a decision, he or she cannot be blamed for it, nor can they take credit for it.
Therefore, the key is whether the leader had the opportunity to weigh the pros and cons and make the right decision on behalf of the nation.
De Gaulle should therefore certainly be on any list of great leaders.
Almost single-handedly, he led France out of the post-WWII decline.
After regaining power in 1958, he once again saved his country, suppressing two coup attempts, ending the Algerian War, and drafting the Constitution of the Fifth Republic.
Like British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, de Gaulle provided the French with a new world view, establishing their position in the post-war global order.
In fact, the long-term impact of de Gaulle and Churchill in shaping their respective national worldviews was somewhat excessive.
Their successors for years afterward viewed the world — and France's role in it — through the lens of constrained rationality and distorted decision-making.
The results were that the leaders after the two countries could never achieve accomplishments that could match those of the two great leaders.
But there was still one British Prime Minister who could match them: she was Margaret Thatcher, a very controversial figure, with as many people who liked her as those who disliked her.
Even her resignation 25 years ago was due to resistance from her own cabinet and party.
But you don't need to please everyone to be a great leader.
In fact, even Thatcher's critics could not deny her influence.
As the first female Prime Minister of the United Kingdom and also one of the earliest female Prime Ministers in other countries, Thatcher helped reverse the economic decline of Britain.
Moreover, her attack on overly powerful trade unions enhanced the manageability of the nation during a time when it seemed to be sliding into chaos and disorder.
Given this, she undoubtedly has the right to be considered a candidate for the title of "Great Leader."
Similarly, although far from flawless, Deng in China also qualifies as a great leader.
Aside from assisting Mao in doing evil, Deng played a decisive role in ordering the 1989 Tiananmen Square massacre.
But Deng also invigorated the market, leading China onto an unprecedented path of development and prosperity that ultimately lifted hundreds of millions of Chinese out of poverty.
Many people regard Singapore's founder and long-serving prime minister Lee Kuan Yew as very great, although he might have hoped to showcase his talents on a bigger stage.
In fact, the size of a country seems not to affect a person's ability to become a great leader.
I made no disrespectful remarks when I said that a country as small as Luxembourg is unlikely to produce a great leader, especially since the country's political climate is generally not very controversial.
Meanwhile, the vast territory of the United States is sufficient to serve as a breeding ground for great leaders.
Some presidents have indeed achieved a lot.
Harry Truman and Dwight Eisenhower — — though not intellectual giants — — displayed outstanding judgment in establishing the postwar international order that supported world peace for decades.
Others, including Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton, possess exceptional talent — — the art of persuasion and inspiring people.
John F. Kennedy was skilled in both areas.
He accomplished a great task: defusing the Cuban Missile Crisis.
His inspirational talent was unparalleled; in fact, his assassination after his death solidified the tradition he left behind.
In South Africa, no one has yet been deemed a great figure after Mandela's death, as Mandela embodied courage, authority, and graceful magnanimity.
In fact, he was the most charming and appealing leader I have ever met; the other two — former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former U.S. Secretary of State Colin Powell — were either African or African American.
So what about today?
The only one who qualifies to claim greatness is the de facto leader of the EU, German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Like former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, she was often underestimated at first, but made few mistakes when making important decisions.
Kohl set generous terms for German unification; Merkel opposed Putin during his invasion of Ukraine and took a tolerant stance on the immigration crisis.
I think Marx and Tolstoy were wrong.
Political leaders — the exercisers of political power — can change the situation, for better or worse.
Merkel is the most obvious example today, guiding Europe in facing high-stakes survival crises.
